# SNOWPIERCER: ETERNAL ENGINE — Comprehensive TODO

> **Repo:** NJHFinanceHub/TrainGame
> **Purpose:** Master task list for GasTown Mayor to decompose and assign to agents.
> **Priority Levels:** P0 (blocks everything), P1 (core gameplay), P2 (important), P3 (polish/nice-to-have)

---

## 1. PLAYER CHARACTER

### 1.1 Protagonist Definition — P0
- [ ] Define protagonist identity: named character vs. custom character creator
- [ ] If custom: define character creation options (gender, appearance, body type, voice)
- [ ] If named: write character backstory, motivation, personality traits
- [ ] Define protagonist's role in the Tail before the game starts (how long on the train, what they lost)
- [ ] Decide: voice acted or silent protagonist
  - If voice acted: define voice direction, emotional range, number of lines estimate
  - If silent: define how player personality is expressed (dialogue choices, actions)
- [ ] Define starting stats/attributes for the protagonist
- [ ] Define protagonist's unique ability or trait that justifies why THEY lead the push forward

### 1.2 Character Progression System — P0
- [ ] Design stat system: define core attributes (e.g., Strength, Endurance, Cunning, Charisma, Perception, Survival)
- [ ] Define how stats affect gameplay:
  - Strength → melee damage, carry weight, forced entry
  - Endurance → cold resistance, stamina pool, hunger rate
  - Cunning → stealth effectiveness, lockpicking, crafting quality
  - Charisma → dialogue options, faction rep gains, companion morale
  - Perception → hidden item detection, enemy awareness range, environmental cues
  - Survival → resource efficiency, medicine effectiveness, Kronole resistance
- [ ] Design leveling system: XP-based, milestone-based (per car/zone), or hybrid
- [ ] Define XP sources: combat, exploration, quest completion, moral choices, stealth
- [ ] Design skill tree structure:
  - Combat branch (melee specialization, weapon mastery, counter-attacks, crowd control)
  - Stealth branch (silent movement, pickpocketing, disguise effectiveness, silent takedowns)
  - Survival branch (crafting efficiency, cold resistance, resource scavenging, medicine brewing)
  - Leadership branch (companion buffs, faction diplomacy, crowd manipulation, intimidation)
  - Engineer branch (hacking, trap-setting, environmental manipulation, lock bypassing)
- [ ] Define skill point acquisition rate — 1 per level? Per zone? Per major quest?
- [ ] Define max level / soft cap
- [ ] Design perk system: passive bonuses unlocked at level thresholds or via specific achievements
  - Example perks: "Tail Survivor" (reduced hunger rate), "Kronole Tolerance" (reduced addiction buildup), "Silver Tongue" (extra dialogue options with First Class)
- [ ] Define respec mechanic — can the player reallocate skill points? At what cost?
- [ ] Balance progression curve: player should feel weak in Zone 1, competent by Zone 3, powerful by Zone 5, and challenged again in Zones 6-7

### 1.3 Movement & Traversal — P1
- [ ] Define base movement: walk speed, sprint speed, crouch speed, prone/crawl
- [ ] Climbing system: ladders, pipes, shelving, stacked bunks — define what surfaces are climbable
- [ ] Vent crawling: define vent network system per car, size constraints, can enemies follow?
- [ ] Rooftop access: can the player go on top of the train? Define when/how
  - Wind resistance mechanic at speed
  - Cold exposure timer while outside
  - Car-to-car rooftop traversal as alternate route
- [ ] Under-car traversal: maintenance catwalks beneath the train floor
- [ ] Jumping: limited or none? (Tight corridors make jumping weird — consider contextual mantling instead)
- [ ] Swimming: any water cars (aquarium breach, flooded sections)?
- [ ] Sliding/dodging: combat dodge roll or sidestep given narrow corridors?
- [ ] Ladder/climbing speed affected by carry weight and injuries

### 1.4 Death & Respawn — P0
- [ ] Define death mechanic: permadeath? Checkpoint-based? Save-anywhere?
- [ ] Checkpoint placement: per car entry? Mid-car for long cars? Before boss fights?
- [ ] Define what is lost on death: nothing (reload), some resources, progress in current car?
- [ ] Companion permadeath: separate from player death?
- [ ] Define "downed" state before full death (can companions revive?)
- [ ] Injury system: non-lethal damage that persists (broken arm = reduced melee, leg injury = slower movement) until healed
- [ ] Cold death: separate mechanic — freezing is a gradual process with escalating debuffs before death

---

## 2. COMPANION SYSTEM

### 2.1 Core Companion Mechanics — P1
- [ ] Define max party size (recommendation: 2 companions + player = 3 total, keeps corridors manageable)
- [ ] Define total recruitable companion count (recommendation: 12-15 across all zones, 8-10 survivable)
- [ ] Can companions permanently die? Define permadeath triggers:
  - Death in combat
  - Consequences of moral choices
  - Faction betrayal
  - Scripted narrative deaths
- [ ] Companion AI behavior modes: aggressive, defensive, passive, hold position
- [ ] Companion pathfinding in tight train corridors — they must not block the player
- [ ] Companion inventory: separate or shared with player?
- [ ] Companion equipment: can they be equipped with weapons/armor?

### 2.2 Companion Roster — P1
- [ ] Design at minimum 12 unique companions across all zones:

| # | Name | Zone Found | Class/Role | Combat Style | Unique Ability |
|---|------|-----------|------------|-------------|----------------|
| 1 | TBD | Tail | Brawler | Unarmed/blunt | Rally nearby Tailies in combat |
| 2 | TBD | Tail | Medic | Support/knife | Field medicine, drug crafting |
| 3 | TBD | Tail | Scout | Stealth/shiv | Vent navigation, lockpicking |
| 4 | TBD | Third Class | Engineer | Traps/tools | Hack systems, disable security |
| 5 | TBD | Third Class | Laborer | Heavy melee | Break through barricades, carry extra weight |
| 6 | TBD | Second Class | Bureaucrat | Non-combat | Forge documents, political access |
| 7 | TBD | Second Class | Teacher | Ranged/support | Child NPC interactions, intel gathering |
| 8 | TBD | Working Spine | Mechanic | Improvised weapons | Repair/sabotage train systems |
| 9 | TBD | First Class | Defector | Swordsmanship | First Class disguise access |
| 10 | TBD | First Class | Entertainer | Distraction | Create diversions, social manipulation |
| 11 | TBD | Sanctum | Ex-Priest | Kronole abilities | Order of the Engine intel |
| 12 | TBD | Sanctum | Jackboot Deserter | Military combat | Armory access, tactical leadership |

- [ ] Write full backstory for each companion (minimum 500 words each)
- [ ] Define each companion's personal quest line (3-5 quests each)
- [ ] Define companion relationship arcs — what builds trust, what breaks it

### 2.3 Loyalty & Relationship System — P2
- [ ] Design loyalty meter: hidden or visible to player?
- [ ] Define loyalty thresholds: acquaintance → ally → trusted → devoted (or equivalent)
- [ ] Define loyalty-affecting events: moral choices, dialogue, gifts, quest outcomes, faction alignment
- [ ] Companion conflicts: what happens when two companions disagree? Can you lose one by siding with the other?
- [ ] Romance system: yes/no decision
  - If yes: how many romanceable companions? Any restrictions?
  - Romance should not gate gameplay-critical content
- [ ] Companion departure conditions: low loyalty, faction betrayal, moral dealbreakers
- [ ] Companion-specific dialogue per car (at minimum for story-critical cars)

---

## 3. DIALOGUE SYSTEM

### 3.1 Dialogue Architecture — P0
- [ ] Define dialogue system type: branching tree, hub-and-spoke, or dynamic/procedural
- [ ] Define max dialogue options per node (recommendation: 4 — direct, diplomatic, aggressive, investigate)
- [ ] Design skill checks in dialogue:
  - Charisma checks for persuasion
  - Cunning checks for deception/manipulation
  - Perception checks for detecting lies
  - Strength checks for intimidation
  - Engineer checks for technical arguments
- [ ] Define skill check visibility: show required stat and pass/fail chance? Or hidden?
- [ ] Timed dialogue decisions: any conversations where silence = a choice? Define timeout behavior.
- [ ] Define dialogue consequence system: immediate, delayed, or both?
- [ ] NPC memory: do NPCs remember what you said to them? How far back?
- [ ] Interrupted dialogue: can combat or events interrupt conversations? How to resume?

### 3.2 Dialogue Content Scope — P1
- [ ] Estimate total word count for all dialogue (target range for scope)
- [ ] Define dialogue density per zone:
  - Tail: sparse, desperate, short exchanges
  - Third Class: functional, transactional
  - Second Class: verbose, political, layered
  - First Class: performative, manipulative
  - Sanctum: ritualistic, cryptic
  - Engine: revelatory, philosophical
- [ ] Write key NPC dialogue trees (priority: quest givers, faction leaders, companions, bosses, Wilford)
- [ ] Define bark/ambient dialogue system for non-interactive NPCs
- [ ] Propaganda PA system: define recurring train announcements per zone

### 3.3 Persuasion/Intimidation/Deception Mechanics — P1
- [ ] Design social combat system: can the player "win" encounters purely through dialogue?
- [ ] Define which encounters can be fully bypassed via dialogue
- [ ] Bribery mechanics: what can be offered, how does it interact with inventory?
- [ ] Blackmail system: collect intel → use in dialogue → force compliance
- [ ] Interrogation mechanics for captured enemies or NPCs
- [ ] Lying system: can the player lie? Can they be caught? Consequences of being caught?

---

## 4. ECONOMY & CRAFTING

### 4.1 Resource Taxonomy — P0
- [ ] Define all resource types and where they're found:

| Resource | Found In | Used For | Rarity |
|----------|----------|----------|--------|
| Metal Scrap | Tail, Third, Spine | Weapon crafting, repairs | Common |
| Cloth/Fabric | All zones | Bandages, cold protection, disguises | Common |
| Protein Blocks | Tail | Food (low quality) | Common in Tail |
| Fresh Food | Second+ | Food (high quality), trading | Rare |
| Medicine (Basic) | Third+ | Heal minor injuries, cure disease | Uncommon |
| Medicine (Advanced) | First+ | Surgery, major healing | Rare |
| Kronole (Raw) | All zones | Crafting, combat buffs, trading | Uncommon |
| Kronole (Refined) | Kronole Network | Stronger buffs, explosive crafting | Rare |
| Electronics | Spine, Second+ | Hacking tools, surveillance devices | Uncommon |
| Chemicals | Spine labs | Poison, medicine, Kronole refinement | Rare |
| Luxury Items | First Class | Trading, bribery, faction rep | Rare |
| Ammunition | Armory, Jackboots | Ranged weapons | Very Rare |
| Blueprints | Hidden/quest | Unlock new crafting recipes | Very Rare |
| Engine Parts | Spine, Sanctum | Endgame crafting, critical quest items | Legendary |

- [ ] Define carry weight / inventory slot system
- [ ] Define resource stacking limits
- [ ] Define resource degradation (does food spoil? Do chemicals decay?)

### 4.2 Crafting System — P1
- [ ] Define crafting station types and locations:
  - Improvised Workbench (Tail) — basic weapons, bandages
  - Machine Shop (Third Class) — intermediate weapons, tools
  - Chemistry Station (Spine) — medicine, poisons, Kronole refinement
  - Electronics Bench (Spine/Second) — hacking tools, surveillance
  - Armorer's Station (Armory) — advanced weapons, armor reinforcement
  - Tailor's Station (First Class) — disguises, cold gear
- [ ] Define full crafting recipe list (minimum 50 recipes across all stations):
  - Weapons: pipe club, shiv, reinforced axe, crossbow, nail bat, shock baton, Kronole grenade
  - Armor: padded vest, metal plate guard, insulated coat, riot shield
  - Tools: lockpick set, hacking device, grappling hook, torch, signal flare
  - Consumables: bandage, medkit, antidote, Kronole dose, molotov, smoke bomb, poison vial
  - Disguises: Third Class uniform, Jackboot armor, Second Class suit, First Class formal wear, Order robes
  - Special: cold suit (exterior traversal), EMP device, explosive charge, radio transmitter
- [ ] Define crafting skill requirements — does player need minimum stats to craft certain items?
- [ ] Define crafting time — instant or requires waiting?
- [ ] Define crafting failure chance — based on skill level?
- [ ] Companion crafting: can companions craft? Auto-craft?
- [ ] Weapon modification system: add attachments, improve stats, change damage type

### 4.3 Weapon & Armor Tiers — P1
- [ ] Define weapon tier system:
  - Tier 1 (Improvised): Found/crafted in Tail. Low damage, breaks fast.
  - Tier 2 (Functional): Third Class workshops. Moderate stats.
  - Tier 3 (Military): Jackboot armory. High damage, durable.
  - Tier 4 (Specialized): Unique weapons from quests/bosses. Special effects.
  - Tier 5 (Legendary): One-of-a-kind. Endgame.
- [ ] Define weapon categories: blunt, bladed, piercing, ranged, thrown, explosive
- [ ] Define armor system: head, torso, legs, hands — or simplified slots?
- [ ] Define armor stats: damage reduction, cold resistance, noise level, movement penalty
- [ ] Define weapon degradation curve per tier
- [ ] Define repair costs and requirements per tier
- [ ] Weapon visual progression: should look more refined as tiers increase

### 4.4 Trading & Barter Economy — P1
- [ ] Define barter system rules — no universal currency, zone-specific value
  - Tail: protein blocks, favors, information
  - Third Class: rations, scrap, work vouchers
  - Second Class: luxury items, medicine, influence
  - First Class: secrets, blackmail, rare goods, Kronole
- [ ] Define price fluctuation: does supply/demand change based on player actions?
- [ ] Define merchant/trader NPCs per zone (minimum 2 per zone)
- [ ] Define haggling mechanic: Charisma-based? Mini-game? Flat rates?
- [ ] Black market system: Kronole Network operates across all zones, premium prices, exclusive items
- [ ] Stolen goods: can player sell stolen items? Consequences if caught?
- [ ] Faction discounts: aligned factions offer better rates

---

## 5. STEALTH SYSTEM

### 5.1 Core Stealth Mechanics — P1
- [ ] Detection model: line of sight + sound-based
- [ ] Define sight detection:
  - Cone of vision per enemy type
  - Distance-based detection (near = instant, far = gradual)
  - Lighting affects detection (dark = harder to spot)
  - Movement speed affects visibility (crouching < walking < sprinting)
- [ ] Define sound detection:
  - Footstep noise by surface type and movement speed
  - Combat noise radius
  - Environmental noise masking (machinery, PA announcements)
  - Player-created distractions (thrown objects, companion diversions)
- [ ] Detection meter: visible indicator showing enemy awareness (unaware → suspicious → alerted → combat)
- [ ] Alert propagation: how does one enemy alerting affect nearby enemies?
- [ ] Alert states per car: can a car go to lockdown? How does it reset?
- [ ] Hiding spots: under bunks, inside lockers, behind machinery, in vents
- [ ] Body discovery: unconscious/dead bodies found → raises alert

### 5.2 Disguise System — P2
- [ ] Define disguise crafting/acquisition per zone
- [ ] Disguise effectiveness by zone:
  - Third Class uniform: free movement in Third Class, suspicious in Second+
  - Jackboot armor: free movement in security areas, NPCs may test you
  - Second Class suit: access to Second Class
  - First Class formal: access to First Class (but behavior must match)
  - Order robes: access to Sanctum
- [ ] Disguise failure conditions: wrong behavior, staying too long, recognized by specific NPCs, carrying wrong items
- [ ] Disguise durability: do they degrade? Can they be blown by combat?
- [ ] NPC challenge system: NPCs may question disguised player, requiring dialogue skill checks
- [ ] Zone-specific behaviors while disguised (must act differently in First Class vs Third Class)

### 5.3 Non-Lethal Options — P1
- [ ] Stealth takedowns: grab from behind, choke hold, knockout — define animation/timing
- [ ] Non-lethal weapons: stun baton, tranquilizer crossbow bolt, sleep gas
- [ ] Pacifist route viability: can the ENTIRE game be completed non-lethally?
  - If not entirely, define which encounters REQUIRE lethal force
- [ ] Unconscious NPC behavior: how long are they out? Can they be restrained? Do they wake and sound alarm?
- [ ] Consequences of lethal vs non-lethal: faction rep impact, companion reactions, narrative branches

---

## 6. EXPLORATION & SECRETS

### 6.1 Collectibles System — P2
- [ ] Define collectible types:
  - **Train Logs:** Written records from passengers/crew. Lore and worldbuilding.
  - **Audio Recordings:** Pre-freeze memories, crew communications, Wilford's private recordings.
  - **Artifacts:** Physical objects from the old world (photos, books, technology).
  - **Blueprints:** Unlock crafting recipes (see Section 4).
  - **Faction Intel:** Documents that reveal faction secrets, usable in dialogue/quests.
  - **Passenger Manifest Pages:** Piece together who's on the train, reveal hidden connections.
- [ ] Define total collectible count per type (recommendation: 200-300 total across all types)
- [ ] Define collectible placement rules: some obvious, some hidden, some gated behind skills/factions
- [ ] Collectible journal/codex UI — how does the player review collected items?
- [ ] Collectible completion rewards: per zone, per type, total completion

### 6.2 Hidden & Secret Cars — P2
- [ ] Design 7-10 secret cars not accessible on the main path:
  - **The Bunker Car:** Survivalist who sealed themselves off. Unique weapons/supplies.
  - **The Ghost Car:** Seemingly empty, haunted by memories (audio/visual flashbacks).
  - **The Rebel Archive:** Hidden history of every failed revolution.
  - **The Outside Lab:** Scientists who've been secretly sending probes outside.
  - **The Stowaway Car:** People living between the walls of other cars.
  - **The Mirror Car:** Wilford's private blackmail vault — leverage on everyone.
  - **The Prototype:** An experimental car with pre-freeze military technology.
- [ ] Define access requirements for each secret car (faction rep, items, skill checks, quest chains)
- [ ] Secret cars should contain unique rewards not available elsewhere
- [ ] At least 2 secret cars should significantly affect ending availability

### 6.3 Exterior Traversal — P1
- [ ] Design rooftop traversal system:
  - Accessible via roof hatches (specific cars only)
  - Wind resistance: player moves slower, can be knocked off at curves
  - Cold exposure: timer before frostbite debuffs begin
  - Visibility: can scout ahead, spot enemies through skylights
  - Combat on rooftop: extremely dangerous, environmental kills (wind, tunnels, ice)
- [ ] Define cold suit mechanic for extended exterior time
- [ ] Design "Breachman" encounters: NPCs who work on the exterior, potential allies/enemies
- [ ] Exterior story moments: at least 3 scripted exterior sequences
  - Emergency repair during a crisis
  - Bypassing a heavily guarded car from outside
  - Final sequence: seeing the thawing world
- [ ] Car-to-car exterior traversal: skip cars by going over them (risk/reward)

### 6.4 Maintenance Tunnels & Sub-Floor — P2
- [ ] Design under-car crawlspace system connecting adjacent cars
- [ ] Define what's found below: pipes, wiring, smuggler caches, rats, trapped passengers
- [ ] Sub-floor as stealth bypass: slower but undetected
- [ ] Sub-floor hazards: steam leaks, electrical shorts, structural collapses
- [ ] Not all cars have accessible sub-floors — define which do

### 6.5 Window & Exterior Viewing System — P2
- [ ] Windows exist in all zones except Tail
- [ ] Define what's visible outside per zone/story progression:
  - Early game: nothing but white, frozen wasteland
  - Mid game: frozen cities, landmarks
  - Late game: signs of thaw — green patches, running water, animals
- [ ] Interactive windows: can be broken (hull breach hazard), looked through for story moments
- [ ] Window as combat mechanic: break window → enemies near it get sucked toward cold / take cold damage

---

## 7. OUTSIDE THE TRAIN / WORLD STATE

### 7.1 World Lore Document — P0
- [ ] Define the year the game takes place
- [ ] Define what caused the freeze (CW-7 climate agent from film? Or original cause?)
- [ ] Define how long the train has been running (recommendation: 7-10 years for societal decay)
- [ ] Define current world state: completely frozen, or beginning to thaw?
- [ ] Define train route: circular? Point-to-point? How long is one loop?
- [ ] Define train population: total passengers, breakdown by class
- [ ] Define other trains: does Big Alice exist? Other trains? Or is Snowpiercer alone?
- [ ] Define pre-freeze world context: nations, technology level, what was lost
- [ ] Write a 2-3 page "History of the Freeze" document for agent reference
- [ ] Define Wilford's backstory: who built the train, why, how did ticket allocation work?

### 7.2 Exterior Environment System — P2
- [ ] Dynamic exterior visuals per train section / story progression
- [ ] Weather system visible through windows: blizzards, clear skies, aurora borealis
- [ ] Temperature display: external temp shown on UI as worldbuilding element
- [ ] Frozen landmarks: recognizable cities/structures visible at specific points in the loop
- [ ] Thaw progression: subtle environmental changes as story progresses (if thaw is part of narrative)

### 7.3 EVA / Cold Suit Mechanics — P2
- [ ] Define cold suit stats: time limit outside, movement restrictions, combat limitations
- [ ] Cold suit acquisition: where found, can it be upgraded?
- [ ] Define exterior objectives that require cold suit:
  - Repair hull breaches
  - Access cars from outside when interior is blocked
  - Retrieve items from frozen exterior structures (stopped alongside ruins?)
  - Endgame: exit the train entirely
- [ ] Frostbite system: exposed extremities → progressive debuffs → death

---

## 8. DIFFICULTY & ACCESSIBILITY

### 8.1 Difficulty Settings — P2
- [ ] Define difficulty tiers:
  - **Passenger:** Story focus. Reduced combat difficulty, generous resources, no companion permadeath.
  - **Survivor:** Balanced. Standard resource scarcity, moderate combat, companion permadeath on.
  - **Eternal Engine:** Hard. Scarce resources, aggressive AI, all permadeath active, no highlighted items.
  - **Mr. Wilford:** Nightmare. One save slot, extreme scarcity, enemies deal massive damage, no HUD.
- [ ] Define per-difficulty modifiers: enemy health, damage, detection range, resource spawn rates, crafting costs
- [ ] Adaptive difficulty option: subtle adjustment based on death count per zone (optional toggle)
- [ ] Can difficulty be changed mid-game?

### 8.2 Accessibility Options — P1
- [ ] Full subtitle system with speaker identification and sound descriptions
- [ ] Subtitle size options (small, medium, large, extra large)
- [ ] Colorblind modes: protanopia, deuteranopia, tritanopia
- [ ] High contrast mode for UI elements
- [ ] Screen reader support for menus (future consideration)
- [ ] Full control remapping: keyboard, mouse, controller
- [ ] One-handed controller layout option
- [ ] Toggle vs hold options for: sprint, crouch, aim
- [ ] Camera shake intensity slider
- [ ] Motion blur toggle
- [ ] Screen flash intensity reduction
- [ ] Auto-aim assist toggle and strength slider
- [ ] Text-to-speech for dialogue (if not voice acted)
- [ ] Dyslexia-friendly font option

---

## 9. TUTORIAL & ONBOARDING

### 9.1 Tutorial Design — P1
- [ ] Tutorial must feel organic — NO tutorial pop-ups breaking immersion
- [ ] Cars 1-5 serve as progressive tutorial:
  - Car 1: Movement, camera, interaction (pick up items, open containers, read notes)
  - Car 2: Crafting introduction (make first improvised tool)
  - Car 3: Combat basics (unarmed → first weapon, blocking, dodging)
  - Car 4: Moral choice tutorial (small-stakes choice to teach the system)
  - Car 5: Quest/objective system, companion recruitment, faction introduction
- [ ] Environmental teaching: use level design to teach mechanics (narrow path forces crouch, dark room forces torch use)
- [ ] Companion dialogue as tutorial: companions explain systems in-character
- [ ] New mechanics in later zones introduced via:
  - NPC demonstrations
  - Environmental necessity (MUST use the system to progress)
  - Companion suggestions
- [ ] Optional "advanced tips" loading screen hints for later mechanics
- [ ] Practice rooms: can the player return to The Pit (Car 3) to practice combat?

### 9.2 Tooltip & Hint System — P2
- [ ] Context-sensitive tooltips: appear only when relevant, fade after first use
- [ ] Hint system: if player is stuck >3 minutes, subtle environmental cue
- [ ] Hint frequency tied to difficulty level (more hints on Passenger, none on Mr. Wilford)
- [ ] Disable all hints toggle

---

## 10. AUDIO & MUSIC

### 10.1 Music Direction — P2
- [ ] Define overall musical identity:
  - Industrial/mechanical base: rhythmic clanking, metallic resonance
  - Zone-specific overlays:
    - Tail: Sparse. Droning. Percussive with found-object sounds.
    - Third Class: Working rhythm. Repetitive mechanical beats.
    - Second Class: Subdued strings. Faded elegance.
    - First Class: Orchestral. Lavish but unsettling undertones.
    - Sanctum: Choral. Hymnal. Organ drones.
    - Engine: Pure mechanical symphony. The Engine IS the music.
- [ ] Adaptive music system:
  - Exploration → low intensity ambient
  - Detection/suspicion → tension layer added
  - Combat → full intensity, percussion-driven
  - Post-combat → gradual wind-down
  - Moral choice → music drops to near-silence, isolated tones
- [ ] Boss fight themes: unique musical motifs for each zone boss (7 total)
- [ ] Title screen music: the sound of the train itself, building into a theme
- [ ] Credits music: varies based on ending achieved

### 10.2 Sound Design — P1
- [ ] Constant train ambiance layer (never silent):
  - Wheel-on-rail rhythm (varies with speed and curves)
  - Metal creaking and groaning
  - Distant mechanical hum from the Engine
  - Wind against the exterior hull
- [ ] Per-zone ambient design:
  - Tail: dripping water, coughing, whispered conversations, rats
  - Third Class: machinery, PA announcements, boots on metal, steam
  - Second Class: muffled conversations, clinking glasses, distant music
  - First Class: orchestral music, laughter, champagne, fountain water
  - Sanctum: chanting, echoing footsteps, incense crackling
  - Engine: overwhelming mechanical symphony, rhythmic pistons
- [ ] Combat audio: impact sounds per weapon type, armor clanks, grunts, bone crunching
- [ ] Environmental sounds: door mechanisms, pressure seals, hull breach wind howl
- [ ] UI sounds: menu navigation, item pickup, quest update, level up

### 10.3 Voice Acting Scope — P1
- [ ] Decision: fully voice acted, partially voice acted, or text-only?
- [ ] If voice acted: estimate total VO lines per character category:
  - Protagonist: ~2000 lines (if voiced)
  - Major NPCs (companions, faction leaders, bosses): ~500 lines each
  - Minor NPCs: ~50 lines each
  - Ambient/bark NPCs: ~10 lines each
  - PA system announcements: ~50 unique messages
- [ ] Casting direction notes per major character
- [ ] Language: English primary, plan for localization (see Section 16)

---

## 11. UI/HUD DESIGN

### 11.1 HUD Elements — P1
- [ ] Health bar: segmented (body part damage?) or single bar?
- [ ] Stamina bar: drain during sprint, combat, climbing
- [ ] Cold exposure indicator: temperature gauge when in cold zones
- [ ] Hunger meter: gradual drain, affects stamina regen
- [ ] Morale indicator: party morale status (if companion system active)
- [ ] Kronole addiction meter: visible only if player has used Kronole
- [ ] Ammo/weapon durability indicator
- [ ] Detection indicator: stealth awareness meter when enemies are near
- [ ] Compass/direction indicator: subtle, always pointing toward the Engine (forward)
- [ ] Interaction prompts: context-sensitive (pick up, talk, open, examine, hack)
- [ ] Damage direction indicator: show where hits are coming from
- [ ] HUD customization: toggle individual elements, opacity slider, size options
- [ ] Minimal HUD mode: only show indicators when relevant (e.g., health only when damaged)

### 11.2 Train Map / Progress Visualization — P1
- [ ] SIGNATURE FEATURE: Full train diagram showing all 100+ cars as a linear map
  - Current position highlighted
  - Visited cars marked with status (cleared, allied, hostile, locked)
  - Zone colors matching art direction
  - Scrollable/zoomable
  - Toggle: show/hide car names, faction control, resources found
- [ ] Mini-map: top-down view of current car showing rooms, doors, enemies (if scouted)
- [ ] Map fog of war: unvisited areas hidden until explored or intel gathered
- [ ] Map markers: quest objectives, points of interest, companion locations, merchants
- [ ] Car detail view: click on a car in the train map to see description, status, resources, NPCs

### 11.3 Menus & Screens — P1
- [ ] Inventory screen: grid or list? Weight display, sorting, filtering, comparison
- [ ] Character screen: stats, skills, perks, equipped items, status effects
- [ ] Quest log: active/completed/failed quests, main quest vs side quests, tracking toggle
- [ ] Faction screen: reputation bars for all factions, relationship summary
- [ ] Companion screen: loyalty, equipment, skills, personal quest progress
- [ ] Crafting screen: available recipes, required materials, station requirements
- [ ] Codex/journal: lore entries, collectibles tracker, passenger manifest progress
- [ ] Settings: video, audio, controls, accessibility, gameplay, HUD customization
- [ ] Photo mode (future consideration)

---

## 12. NARRATIVE GAPS

### 12.1 Antagonist Design — P0
- [ ] **Wilford (or equivalent):** Full character brief — personality, backstory, motivation, relationship to the Engine
  - Is Wilford alive? A legend? A figurehead for someone else?
  - Define Wilford's argument: why the class system is "necessary"
  - Wilford must be compelling, not cartoonishly evil
- [ ] **Mid-game antagonist:** The player needs someone to oppose before reaching Wilford
  - Recommendation: Head of Jackboots or a Sanctum leader who operates independently
  - This character should appear in Zone 2-3 and persist until Zone 5-6
  - Personal connection to the player if possible
- [ ] **Zone bosses:** Full character briefs for all 7 zone bosses
  - Name, backstory, fighting style, motivation, potential for non-combat resolution
- [ ] **The Mole:** Is there a traitor in the player's party? Define who and why.

### 12.2 Named NPCs — P1
- [ ] Create at minimum 30 named NPCs beyond companions and antagonists:
  - 5 per zone × 6 non-Engine zones = 30 minimum
  - Each needs: name, role, personality, 1-2 quests, faction alignment
- [ ] Key named NPCs (require full character sheets):
  - The Elder (Tail leader who sends you forward)
  - The Black Marketeer (appears in multiple zones)
  - The Kronole King/Queen (drug network leader)
  - The Breachman Captain (exterior workers leader)
  - The Archivist (keeper of train history)
  - The Surgeon (performs "treatments" in Second Class)
  - The Entertainer (First Class performer who knows secrets)
  - The High Priest (Order of the Engine leader)
  - The Child (taken from the Tail, now in the Engine — the emotional core)

### 12.3 Previous Revolution Backstory — P0
- [ ] Write full account of the last failed revolution (the one Curtis led, or equivalent)
- [ ] Define how many revolutions have been attempted (recommendation: 3-4)
- [ ] Each past revolution should have:
  - Leader's name and fate
  - How far they got
  - Why they failed
  - What changed on the train as a result
  - Physical evidence the player finds in specific cars
- [ ] The player's revolution should be informed by (and learn from) past failures
- [ ] At least one survivor of a past revolution should be a recruitable companion or key NPC

### 12.4 Timeline & World State — P0
- [ ] Define complete timeline:
  - Year of the freeze
  - Year the train launched
  - Year of each past revolution
  - Year of the game's events
  - Key events between (disasters, births, deaths, policy changes)
- [ ] Define train demographics:
  - Total population at launch vs now
  - Birth rate, death rate
  - Population per class
  - How many Jackboots, Order members, etc.
- [ ] Define the original ticket system and class assignment
- [ ] Define what happens to the dead (ceremony? Recycling? Ejected?)

### 12.5 Moral Choice Catalog — P1
- [ ] Design and document ALL major moral choices (minimum 20 across the game):

| # | Car(s) | Choice | Option A | Option B | Consequences |
|---|--------|--------|----------|----------|--------------|
| 1 | 4 | Children's rations | Steal food | Protect children | Hunger vs. morality, Tailie rep |
| 2 | 9 | First blockade | Fight through | Find alternate path | Combat vs. stealth, casualties |
| 3 | 25 | The Brig | Free prisoners | Leave them | Gain allies vs. maintain cover |
| 4 | 28 | Hydroponics | Sabotage food | Protect production | Weaken First Class vs. feed everyone |
| ... | ... | ... | ... | ... | ... |

- [ ] Each choice must affect at least 2 of: faction rep, companion loyalty, accessible cars, ending path
- [ ] No "obviously correct" answers — both options should have real trade-offs
- [ ] Choices compound: late-game options should reference/be affected by early choices
- [ ] Track choice flags in save system for ending calculation

